Best to wrap at the `:` before wrapping elsewhere:
```suggestion
theorem birthday_eq_pGame_birthday (x : Game) :
    ∃ y : PGame.{u}, ⟦y⟧ = x ∧ y.birthday = birthday x :=
```
Could you add `birthday_ofNat` too, using `no_index (OfNat.ofNat n)`?
What's `no_index`? Does `Game` even have an `OfNat.ofNat` instance? I don't believe we use it anywhere else in it's API.

> What's `no_index`?

In practice, a workaround for janky behavior by `simp` around `ofNat`

> Does `Game` even have an `OfNat.ofNat` instance?

Good question; I assumed it would have since it seems to have a `NatCast`, and those usually come together. I didn't actually check though. Is there an `AddMonoidWithOne` instance?

Yes, it exists:
```
#synth OfNat SetTheory.Game 37
```

Is there any theorem saying `OfNat.ofNat n = ↑n`? There's [Nat.cast_eq_ofNat](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Nat/Cast/Defs.html#Nat.cast_eq_ofNat) but only for naturals greater than 2.

Also, should `birthday_ofNat` take in a `[OfNat Game n]` argument? I don't believe the instance can be inferred in general.
No, it should assume `[n.AtLeastTwo]`. The theorem you want is then true by rfl, so you can prove the whole thing in terms of the natCast lemma

```suggestion
theorem birthday_neg (x : Game) : (-x).birthday = x.birthday := by
```

```suggestion
theorem toGame_natCast : ∀ n : ℕ, toGame n = n
```

and the `ofNat` lemma too

```suggestion
theorem birthday_ofNat (n : ℕ) [n.AtLeastTwo] :
    birthday (no_index (OfNat.ofNat n)) = OfNat.ofNat n :=
```
Can you add the usual `-- See note` comment that appears before `no_index`/`OfNat` lemmas?
Sorry, I don't think I've ever seen that note. Is there any other theorem I can copy it from?
Searching for `OfNat.ofNat` should find the comment quite quickly
Oh I found it, I think I might have had caps lock on or something.
I think the convention is not to indent here
Can you mention the lemma that links the two definitions?
Should this be a theorem? This is trivial, and you only use it once

The intention of this theorem is that if someone wants to work with `birthday` using the direct infimum definition, they can show that they're not in the trivial and somewhat badly behaved case of `sInf Ø`. Admittedly I'm not sure how often you'll want to do this, but even if it's never, I don't think having this theorem hurts.
In those situations, what we usually do is make the lemma `private`. The rationale is that people shouldn't need this kind of lemma past the API, else there is a problem with the API.

Alright, I'll inline this.

I don't remember if I was the one who added them, but there do exist other lemmas like this for the ordinal API, like [`Ordinal.sub_nonempty`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/SetTheory/Ordinal/Arithmetic.html#Ordinal.sub_nonempty) or [`Ordinal.div_nonempty`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/SetTheory/Ordinal/Arithmetic.html#Ordinal.div_nonempty). Should those be privated / inlined in a separate PR?
Yeah probably
Does this need to be `protected`?
Probably not.
Looks like you referenced twice the same lemma

```suggestion
theorem birthday_eq_pGameBirthday (x : Game) :
```

```suggestion
theorem birthday_quot_le_pGameBirthday (x : PGame) : birthday ⟦x⟧ ≤ x.birthday :=
```

```suggestion
theorem birthday_ordinalToGame (o : Ordinal) : birthday o.toGame = o := by
```
for disambiguation, maybe?

```suggestion
@[simp, norm_cast]
```

```suggestion
@[simp, norm_cast]
```

```suggestion
  sInf (PGame.birthday '' Quotient.mk' ⁻¹' {x})
```
This... doesn't seem to work.
Uh okay

You'd do better to replace the `natCast` field in the `AddCommGroupWithOne` instance above. I think your two proofs here become the `natCast_zero` and `natCast_succ` fields, and then this proof becomes `rfl`.

I'd rather not tweak the `NatCast` instances at this point, since there's an issue with the `PGame` instance that needs to be addressed.

The `NatCast` instance on `PGame` doesn't match the actual mathematical definition. It's directly defined as `0 + 1 + 1 + ...`, which due to how game addition works, leads to it having a left set of different relabellings of `n - 1` rather than the expected `0` through `n - 1`. (Note that the resulting `Game` is the same however).

The actual definition is given by `Ordinal.toPGame` on a natural argument. But replacing it means `(0 : N)` is no longer equal (not even prop-eq) to `0`. That is, unless, we defined it near the start of the file, and redefined `0` and `1` to match. Which feels like a messy solution to me.

I made a thread about this on Zulip in the #mathlib4 channel, can't link it on mobile unfortunately.
Here's the thread: https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/287929-mathlib4/topic/Nat.20.E2.86.92.20PGame.20cast.2C.20again/near/469290453
The conclusion from that thread (or at least what I concluded) was that it's probably better to wait for `IGame` before tweaking any of these instances.
